Description: This shallow reef site, chosen for its exceptional biodiversity, is thought to support the greatest variety of marine life in the National Marine Sanctuary System, including coral, invertebrates, marine plants, fishes, marine mammals, and turtles. We are particularly interested in monitoring reef health, investigating human use patterns, and better understanding marine mammal presence in the area.

An area of high-density humpback whale habitat with significant vessel traffic, located adjacent to the culturally and ecologically important Olowalu Reef. This reef supports a diverse marine ecosystem and acts as a source reef. Humpback whales here exhibit diurnal patterns, staying offshore during the day and moving inshore at night.

A remote bank at the eastern end of the Monument’s boundary with relatively high humpback whale densities. While vessel use and naval activities in this area are not well understood, they are detected. Understanding these activities could be crucial for managing the site if the Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument (PMNM) is designated as a Sanctuary.
